    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a helpful way to visualize it, but I'm a bit worried about the \"any and all losses\" part. It sounds pretty broad. Does that mean I could be on the hook for things that aren't even directly my fault, or is there some way to limit how much they can come after me for?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the \"any and all losses\" part, you say? Well, it's like a goblin's treasure hoard – vast and seemingly endless. But fear not, for there are ways to protect yourself from goblin-sized pitfalls. You see, in the world of NDAs, it's not uncommon to negotiate the terms to ensure that you're not left holding the bag for every little mishap. It's like setting up traps and barriers around your treasure to keep the goblins at bay. You might want to discuss with the Disclosing Party about narrowing down the scope of what you're responsible for, or perhaps setting a cap on the amount you could be liable for. It's all about finding the right balance, like a goblin trying to balance on a tightrope – too much on one side, and you fall into a pit of goblin stew, too little, and you might not be able to defend your castle properly. So, it's worth having a chat with the Disclosing Party to see if there's room for some negotiation.",
